Anonymous Sun 27 Jun 2021 19:03:21 No.39749785 Report
Quoted By: >>39750080
>>39749341
Depends on the story and what sort of experience you want reading it to be. First person is, to me at least, kind of like reading someone's diary. Very intimate and exploratory. Great for building tension and intrigue. Not so good for descriptions and world building. Second person is great for self-insertion, and lends itself well to adventure or smut. Its weakness would be that it makes describing other characters a lot tougher, since you don't have an all-knowing narrator. Third person is the best for anything larger in scope or more epic. It gives you the freedom to jump between perspectives and explain the world and story in greater detail. Might lack the intimacy of the other two forms, but it's also the most popular in literature

>>39749785
I agree that first is very immediate, even when done in the mass market standard of FPOV past tense. If the effect is "reader finds/figures out things at the same time as the protag", then the only challenge is getting the reader to root for the protag. I'd disagree on the worldbuilding. The reader gets the same intimate view of second person, but avoids the problems of losing the reader if the self-insert is too far off of them.
Second? It blends all the weaknesses of first & third person, and chains the writer down to constantly railroading the reader back to the plot. That's also it's strength. If first person is intimate like a line of cocaine, second is freebase or an afternoon with a few rocks of crack.
There's ways to drop the larger potential scope of third person in either first or second, What it loses in the tension of the narrator unwittingly lying to you is gained back in foreshadowing, and the tension of how an obvious event will play out.

Anonymous Sun 27 Jun 2021 22:52:38 No.39754578 Report
Quoted By:
>>39751131
You can, but it's very intrusive unless that IS the plot. In fppov your reader needs to be in the shoes of a character living out your story beats; his or her perspective and monologues ARE the journey. Even the fluff should contribute to his or her development in some way, progressing the plot, or foreshadowing key elements that are retroactively elucidated to or by the protagonist later. You could dedicate a chapter to it, but again, that means dedicating a substantial portion of your story on a fluff piece that only serves as an overture for the author who wouldn't otherwise have that opportunity to show off the actual breadth of their worldbuilding. This works in webcomics, and diehards gobble it up, but making a chapter (or arc) you can arguably presage as "skippable" is poor form.

Now, it can be done in a way that tacitly moves the plot (eg foreshadowing), where the fluff serves as a series of layers around an element you want to stand out—or even more enticing, conceal. Putting your fluff to work is easy enough.
With the former, the fluff presents a turning point in the plot's progression, signaling it in whatever way necessary to communicate that to your reader. You give your fluff a flavor that your readers are reeeally craving, and put your nugget of plotonium in the center; like a first kiss, or that moment when a challenger appears to crash your party (eg your rEaL antagonist's intro). Queue apropos theme: https://youtu.be/FsioumIqpCg
In the latter's case, you subtly plant it within the chapter such that it doesn't quite stand out to your protagonist (to wit, until a later chapter: retroactive plotonium in that case). Think something like a scene in a (made up) Smallville comic where young Clark Kent is on a class trip to a Lexcorp research front where finds himself feeling uneasy, distressed by the sight of an exhibit behind several layers of decontaminating, blast-proof glass & UV screens presenting an innocuous, green pebble from space
